Macedonian referendum on renaming
The people of Macedonia voted last Sunday in a referendum on whether the country's name should be changed to the 'North Macedonia Republic', which would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece which has hindered the country's attempts to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia and claims that the name of its northern neighbour is a requirement on its territory and has therefore prevented Macedonia from joining NATO and the EU.
The two governments concluded an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change of name would undermine the identity of the Slavic majority of Macedonia.
President Ivanov has said that he does not intend to vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has led to doubts as to whether the minimum participation of 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid will be reached.
The question on the ballot in the referendum is: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
However, the supporters of the change of name, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is worth changing the name if it allows Macedonia, one of the countries that was formed when Yugoslavia split up, to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgievska, 79, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of this House have said that they intend to follow the outcome in order for it to be considered decisive.
The change of name requires a majority of two thirds of Parliament.
According to the State Electoral Commission, no irregularities were reported at 1 p.m.
But participation was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66% of registered voters voted.
"I am voting for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital Skopje.
The Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko are voting in the referendum in Macedonia on the change of name, which would open the way for membership of NATO and the European Union, in Stromica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
Outside the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, arranged a small stage and place out chairs in front of the tents set up by those boycotting the referendum.
"We are in favour of NATO and the EU, but we want to go with our heads in the air, not sneak in through the back door," Kavardarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, such as China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, membership of NATO would lead to much-needed investments in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20%.
"I believe that the absolute majority will vote in favour, because over 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," said Zaev when he voted.
He said a "Yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future."
According to a survey published on Monday by the Macedonian Policy Survey Institute, between 30 and 43% of voters were planning to vote in the referendum, which falls within the minimum participation required.
According to another survey conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57 percent of the participants were planning to vote on Sunday.
70 percent of them were going to vote in favour.
For the referendum to count, 50% of registered voters plus one must vote.
If the referendum fails, it will be the first serious setback for the Western Government's policy since it took over last May.
