North Korea says that they will "never" disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's Foreign Minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened their distrust of the United States and it was not possible that it would give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the World Organisation that over the past year North Korea had taken "significant steps to show its goodwill", for example by stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test installations and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances there is no chance that we unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to an approach divided into stages for the nuclear power that would lead to North Korea being rewarded when it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution entirely as Pyongyang had previously done.
Mr Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Mr Kim Jong Un and Mr Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting US President and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, in which Kim promised to work towards "nuclear decommissioning on the Korean Peninsula" while Mr Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the Korean War 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first dismantle its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also turned down negotiations to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "dismantling first" and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose by coercion and even objects to the "declaration to end the war," says Ri.
"The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a pipe dream for those people who lack knowledge of us.
But the problem is that the continuing sanctions deepen our distrust."
Mr Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leaders highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the party to this issue of nuclear disarmament had been South Korea and not the United States, the Korean peninsula's nuclear disarmament would not have come to such an impasse."
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's future ability to reach the US mainland with rockets was inevitable after Mr Evil President Trump called Kim a rocketman on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "fully destroy" North Korea, commended Kim for his courage to take action to disarm, but it said that much work still remains to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
On Wednesday Trump said that he had no time frame for this and said that "if it takes two years, three years or five months", doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
