Harvard students take courses on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has led all doctoral students to improve their sleep habits in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture of studying through caffeine-filled "days".
One academic study found that students at the world’s leading universities are often unsuspecting about the very foundations of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleeping medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he considers to be the first of his kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, "Why can't I know this until now, in my last year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was organised for the first time this year, explains to the students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, and improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university’s health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that the students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In part of the course there is a picture of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, coaches and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part, participants learn how long - term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that this will not change the students' behaviour directly.
But we think they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know about the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in the fact that "day" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
To ensure that you have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain because insomnia puts the brain in a state of starvation and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course and has studied one of his courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course was an eye-opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus-wide course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study programme before starting their studies at the high-performance department.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed and when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can cause you to turn around, leading to sleep problems.
